05359nam a22010215i 9780520960015DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20142014cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209600157 a10.1525/97805209600152doi  a(DE-B1597)520183  a(OCoLC)1102798643  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPN1995.7bJ33.2015 7aPER0040002bisacsh04a791.43/6578223  aLR 535092rvk1 aJacobs, Lea, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFilm Rhythm after Sound :bTechnology, Music, and Performance /cLea Jacobs. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tOnline Film Clips -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- t1. Introduction -- t2. A Lesson with Eisenstein -- t3. Mickey Mousing Reconsidered -- t4. Lubitsch and Mamoulian -- t5. Dialogue Timing and Performance in Hawks -- t6. Afterword -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tFilmography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe seemingly effortless integration of sound, movement, and editing in films of the late 1930s stands in vivid contrast to the awkwardness of the first talkies. Film Rhythm after Sound analyzes this evolution via close examination of important prototypes of early sound filmmaking, as well as contemporary discussions of rhythm, tempo, and pacing. Jacobs looks at the rhythmic dimensions of performance and sound in a diverse set of case studies: the Eisenstein-Prokofiev collaboration Ivan the Terrible, Disney’s Silly Symphonies and early Mickey Mouse cartoons, musicals by Lubitsch and Mamoulian, and the impeccably timed dialogue in Hawks’s films. Jacobs argues that the new range of sound technologies made possible a much tighter synchronization of music, speech, and movement than had been the norm with the live accompaniment of silent films. Filmmakers in the early years of the transition to sound experimented with different technical means of achieving synchronization and employed a variety of formal strategies for creating rhythmically unified scenes and sequences. Music often served as a blueprint for rhythm and pacing, as was the case in mickey mousing, the close integration of music and movement in animation. However, by the mid-1930s, filmmakers had also gained enough control over dialogue recording and editing to utilize dialogue to pace scenes independently of the music track. Jacobs’s highly original study of early sound-film practices provides significant new contributions to the fields of film music and sound studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDialogue in motion pictures. 0aMotion picture music. 0aMotion picturesxProduction and direction. 0aRhythm. 0aSound in motion pictures. 70(DE-601)1041377540(DE-588)4040802-4aMusik2gnd 70(DE-601)1045581050(DE-588)4185670-3aTonfilm2gnd 70(DE-601)10568855X0(DE-588)4132330-0aRhythmus2gnd 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  aanimated films.  aanimation.  acase studies.  adialogue.  adisneys silly symphonies.  aeisenstein-prokofiev collaboration.  afilm and television.  afilm editing.  afilm history.  afilm music.  afilm rhythm.  afilm studies.  afilm.  afilmmaking.  afirst talkies.  aivan the terrible.  amickey mouse cartoons.  amovement in film.  amovies.  amusic track.  amusicals.  apacing.  aperformance and sound.  arhythm.  asound film practices.  asound in film.  asound studies.  asound technologies.  asound.  asynchronized sound.  atechnology.  atempo.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cp